result.execSummary:
The defendant Andrai Alonzo Barrios was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

The court sentenced the defendant to 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive, with credit for 8 days time served.  Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 18 MONTHS.

AS TO COUNT 2 AMENDED
The court sentenced the defendant to 90 DAYS in the House of Correction, consecutive.  Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 18 MONTHS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION
-Serve 40 days (as to count 1) in the House of Correction as Condition Time, STAYED pending review.
-Batterers Intervention program.
-Parenting classes.
-AODA assessment.
-Absolute sobriety.
-Treatment and/or counseling as determined by agent.

Defendant Andrai Alonzo Barrios in court with attorney Colin P. McGinn.  Porchia Sharese Lewand appeared for the State of Wisconsin. CMC. Case set for Jury Trial. Parties have reached a resolution. 

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 2
Pursuant to plea negotiations, on motion of the state, court ordered the Habitual Criminality Repeater DISMISSED. 

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 2
Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Court advised that under 48 USC Section 922(g)(9) the defendant is prohibited from possession of a firearm after conviction of a misdemeanor crime of domestic violence. 

Case adjourned to branch 24 for Sentencing.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for June 2, 2016 at 01:30 pm.
